main.py — Load the nearest .env found at or above the file with python-dotenv, read the Bedrock model id and AWS region from environment variables, and create the FastAPI app with CORS middleware whose origin regex opens it to any localhost or 127.0.0.1 port.
Define Pydantic request and response models typing every payload the API accepts and returns.
Keep a multi-project registry in projects.json with slugified project ids and an active project pointer, auto-creating an untitled project on first use, and let callers create, select, rename, delete, and wipe projects.
Store every human, context, and python text in a content-addressed compile graph persisted as graph.json (graph-<name>.json for non-default names, with slashes in the name encoded as double underscores in the graph filename), accepting slash-nested program names whose every segment matches the flat naming rule and never contains backslashes, parent references, or empty segments, keyed by sha256 hash with created/updated timestamps, links from human to context to python, and a language key on each code snapshot defaulting to python, so going back to an old snapshot restores its whole chain while deletes cascade down through dependent contexts and pythons.
Maintain a phrase memo per graph that remembers how each human line was segmented, snaps phrases to whole word groups so a run of numbers is never split, extracts the refinement a new wording adds via word-level diffing after stripping leading connector words, and remaps phrases back to the memoized segmentation.
Track per-line provenance for every context, numbering each non-blank line and labeling it added, inherited, updated, or manual together with the human phrase it came from, matching updated lines to the closest previous line by difflib similarity of at least 0.72, and for split contexts attributing every non-blank line to the human phrase that motivated it via the llm alone and stamping each entry with a stable phraseId from the graph's phrase registry — graph['phrases'] mapping ids p1, p2, ... from a phrase_seq counter to each phrase's current text and 1-based human line, ensure_phrase reusing the id of an exactly-equal text (refreshing its line) and allocating a new id for new wording so an unchanged phrase keeps its id across recompiles — with api responses hydrating each entry's source string from the registry's current wording without mutating the graph and entries without a phraseId (legacy graphs) passing through byte-identical, stamping line_attribution as llm on every split context node with no read-time backfill, so legacy graphs show no attribution until re-adopted; when a split context is saved by hand, provenance is carried from the previous context by stripped-line-text match preserving each entry's human-phrase source and phraseId, only genuinely new lines invoke the llm line attribution and land as manual entries with an id from their attributed phrase, and a fully-carried save makes zero llm calls.
Materialize the active texts into per-project workspace files (.human, .context, an explain report, and a code file whose extension comes from the stored language of the active snapshot), unlinking stale outputs left under other extensions, and mirror them into the repo-level human and project folders, dropping the mirrored context on the direct route and writing split units as their own files, creating parent directories first for every workspace file and name-derived repo path so nested program names land cleanly.
Build the history tree returned with every files response, humans sorted newest first with their linked contexts and pythons, previews truncated at 72 chars, active flags, roles, and timestamps.
Route every llm stage through claude on aws bedrock using the boto3 bedrock-runtime converse api at temperature 0, with system prompts produced by parametrized builder functions that return the exact original strings for python and otherwise swap in the requested language's label and extension — human-to-context, incremental context update, split decomposition, direct human-to-code — plus one-word triage prompts deciding leaf versus split and direct versus context.
Parse a split context into sections whose header line names the file it compiles to, validated against an extension whitelist (context, py, ts, tsx, js, jsx, mjs, cjs, css, json, html, md, toml, yaml, yml, txt, svg) and allowing forward-slash-nested relative paths with no backslashes or dot-dot segments, attribute each section header to the human phrase that motivated it via an llm json assignment validated to cover every section exactly once and each context line to its phrase via an llm assignment validated to cover every non-blank line — each retried once on invalid output and then raising HTTP 502 "llm attribution failed: <stage>" for the frontend to surface, with no keyword fallback; the section parsing, line numbering, and header regexes imported from attribution.py, a pure sibling module with no FastAPI, llm, or graph dependencies — map each split unit's code lines back to the context line and phrase that motivated them, the llm returning non-overlapping ranges validated to cover every non-blank code line under the same retry-then-502 rule, degenerate single-phrase programs skipping the llm entirely and citing the full human text as source, stored by both compile and adopt, section headers and unit code lines stamped with their phraseId like context lines — each unit entry copying the id of its motivating context line — so responses hydrate every source from the registry's current wording and reword needs no provenance rewrite, on manual split saves re-linked under the new context hash with each entry's contextLine remapped old-to-new by line text (entries whose line was deleted falling back to the section-header entry), and exposed as the split pythonProvenance by concatenating active units' entries sorted by target, every provenance entry carrying an optional contextLine field (the 1-based context line motivating a code line, null where inapplicable), and on the direct path map generated code lines back to verbatim phrases snapped to the human text.
Orchestrate adaptive compilation that reuses cached results for an already-seen human unless forced, asks the shape decision for leaf or split, updates the previous leaf incrementally when the human text changed, and compiles each split section into its own child tagged with its target file, deriving the child's language from the target's own extension and telling non-python units to reference siblings by relative path instead of importing by module name.
Expose filesystem endpoints serving a recursive directory tree capped at depth 12 that skips folders like node_modules and .git, a native windows folder picker driven by a powershell FolderBrowserDialog with a 300 second timeout, and raw file read, write, create, and delete with path and name validation.
Serve rest endpoints for the active graph — root and health, files (which, when the graph has no active human yet and a matching .human file exists under the repo human folder on disk, seeds its response with that file's text as the human plus the sibling .context as a leaf-role context if present, python and history empty, writing nothing on the GET so the first save records those texts through the normal flow, and which exposes the graph's phrases map alongside each provenance entry's phraseId), save persisting edited texts while keeping the previous snapshot's language and routing a manual .context save through the split-preserving path whenever the previous context was split so the program stays split, save-unit taking a name, target, and code — refusing with a 400 unless the active context is split with a section matching the target, recording the code as the active unit python with its language from the target's extension, computing per-line provenance with the llm (one retry, then a 502), and materializing — reword rebinding new human wording to the existing context and python without recompiling — its request carrying optional camelCase oldPhrase and newPhrase fields so that on a split program with both present reword rewrites no stored provenance at all: it only updates the text and 1-based line of every registry entry whose text equals the old phrase and mirrors the change into the phrase memo so the new wording still resolves to its memoized segmentation, every stored link following the new wording automatically through response-time hydration, no llm involved, and with the fields absent (and on leaf and direct programs) behaving exactly as before — checkout, delete, bundle returning the human/context/python trio for a hash, and the compile family (human-to-context, human-to-split, context-to-python, the legacy compile-all, and compile as the primary entry that either stores a short marker context and goes straight to code or takes the context route) accepting an optional language field that defaults to python and rejects unknown values with a 400.
Launch with uvicorn through the fastapi cli (uv run fastapi run main.py), with runtime deps declared in pyproject.toml: fastapi[standard], which bundles uvicorn and pydantic, plus boto3 and python-dotenv.
